Problem 2¶

  • Online ads campaigns are usually organized by Campaign, Ad Group (or Ad Set), and Ads.

  • A campaign can have many ad groups that target different groups of people. Then, inside each ad group, you have the ads that people in that group will see.

  • Before running, you never know which campaign or ad group will be the best. Its normal to launch multiple ad groups and after a few days turn off the ones that are not reaching your goals.

  • The problem is that without attribution you dont know which ad groups to turn off and which to allocate more budget to.

      - Could you quantify the effects of the different Ad Groups?
  - How would you distribute your budget among the different ad groups?

  • Please, provide details about the following topics to be used in the model:

    • Frequency Selected (Daily, Weekly, or Monthly)
    • Variables to use as Media Data (inputs)
    • Criteria used to split between training and validation
    • Variable Transformations

# CTR: Click through rate
# CPC: Cost per Click
# CPM: Cost per thousand impression
# ROI: Return on Investment
campaign_data_p2['CTR'] = campaign_data_p2['Clicks']/campaign_data_p2['Impressions']
campaign_data_p2['CPC'] = campaign_data_p2['Spend']/campaign_data_p2['Clicks']
campaign_data_p2['CPM'] = (campaign_data_p2['Spend']/campaign_data_p2['Impressions'])*1000
campaign_data_p2['ROI'] = campaign_data_p2['Spend']/campaign_data_p2['Total_spend']

  • Brand 2 Ad group 1 & 2 failed in user engagment, however they have large audience, so re-launching campaign with new strategy will definitely have more engagement in future

#I used a simple validation split by time.
#I selected the last 28 days as validation

split_point = pd.Timestamp("2021-12-15") # 28 days to end of data

media_data_train = media_data_raw.loc[:split_point - pd.Timedelta(1,'D')]
media_data_test = media_data_raw.loc[split_point:]

target_train = roi_raw.loc[:split_point - pd.Timedelta(1,'D')]
target_test = roi_raw.loc[split_point:]

costs_train = costs_raw.loc[:split_point - pd.Timedelta(1,'D')].sum(axis=0).loc[media_data_train.columns]

#Using organic data as extra features can give you a more accurate view of your paid media effects.
organic_raw = pd.DataFrame({'organic_search': 0, 'organic_social': 0}, index=media_data_raw.index)
organic_raw['organic_search'] = roi_raw.values/10 + np.random.randint(10000, 100000, organic_raw.shape[0])
organic_raw['organic_social'] = roi_raw.values/10 + np.random.randint(10000, 100000, organic_raw.shape[0])

organic_data_train = organic_raw.loc[:split_point - pd.Timedelta(1,'D')]
organic_data_test = organic_raw.loc[split_point:]

In [370]:
#Finding the right parameters for the model 
#adstock_models = ["adstock", "hill_adstock", "carryover"]
#degrees_season = [1,2,3]

adstock_models = ["hill_adstock"]
degrees_season = [1,2,3]

for model_name in adstock_models:
    for degrees in degrees_season:
        mmm = lightweight_mmm.LightweightMMM(model_name=model_name)
        mmm.fit(media=media_data_train_scaled,
                media_prior=costs_scaled,
                target=target_train_scaled,
                extra_features=organic_data_train_scaled,
                number_warmup=1000,
                number_samples=1000,
                number_chains=1,
                degrees_seasonality=degrees,
                weekday_seasonality=True,
                seasonality_frequency=365,
                seed=SEED)
    
    prediction = mmm.predict(
    media=media_data_test_scaled,
    extra_features=organic_data_test_scaled,
    target_scaler=target_scaler,
    seed=SEED)
    p = prediction.mean(axis=0)

    mape = mean_absolute_percentage_error(target_test.values, p)
    print(f"model_name={model_name} degrees={degrees} MAPE={mape} samples={p[:3]}")
